SIMPLE: spice
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spice
<hw>Spice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>spice</ets>,
<ets>spece</ets>, spice, species, OF. <ets>espice</ets>,
<ets>espece</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧pice</ets> spice,
<ets>esp⟦egrave⟧ce</ets> species, fr. L. <ets>species</ets> particular
sort or kind, a species, a sight, appearance, show, LL., spices, drugs,
etc., of the same sort, fr. L. <ets>specere</ets> to look. See
<er>Spy</er>, and cf. <er>Species</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Species;
kind.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>spices</qex> of penance ben three.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Abstain you from all evil <qex>spice</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Wyclif
(1. Thess,v. 22).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Justice, although it be but one entire virtue, yet is described in
two kinds of <qex>spices</qex>. The one is named justice distributive,
the other is called commutative.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
Elyot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A vegetable production of many kinds, fragrant or
aromatic and pungent to the taste, as pepper, cinnamon, nutmeg, mace,
allspice, ginger, cloves, etc., which are used in cookery and to flavor
sauces, pickles, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hast thou aught in thy purse [bag] any hot <qex>spices</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Piers Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Figuratively, that which enriches or alters the
quality of a thing in a small degree, as spice alters the taste of food;
that which gives zest or pungency; a slight flavoring; a relish; hence,
a small quantity or admixture; a sprinkling; <as>as, a <ex>spice</ex> of
mischief</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So much of the will, with a <qex>spice</qex> of the willful.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spice</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spice
<hw>Spice</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spiced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spicing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
season with spice, or as with spice; to mix aromatic or pungent
substances with; to flavor; to season; <as>as, to <ex>spice</ex> wine;
to <ex>spice</ex> one's words with wit</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She 'll receive thee, but will <qex>spice</qex> thy bread⟦br⟧
With flowery poisons.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fill or impregnate with the odor of
spices.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the <qex>spiced</qex> Indian air, by night.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To render nice or dainty; hence, to render
scrupulous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>spiced</xex>
conscience.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spicebush</ent>⟦br⟧
